Bias triangles are important components in the stability diagrams of quantum dot (QD) devices. Their presence and properties are key indicators of spin physics. However, the quality and availability of data, as well as the subtlety of the physical phenomena of interest, have hindered the development of an automated and bespoke analysis framework. Often, this framework still relies on human labelling and verification. We introduce a feature extraction framework for bias triangles that is built from unsupervised, segmentation-based computer vision methods. This facilitates the direct identification and quantification of physical properties of the former. Thus, the need for human input or large training datasets to inform supervised learning approaches is circumvented, while also enabling the automation of pixelwise shape and feature labelling. In particular, we demonstrate that pauli spin blockade (PSB) detection can be conducted effectively, efficiently, and without any training data as a direct result of this approach.
